latest practice all the company follows .

Config driven UI : Our websites uses config : controlling the UI through the data 

Config-driven UI (CDUI) is a design pattern where the structure, layout, and behavior of a user interface are defined by external configuration files or data, rather than being hard-coded within the application's source code. This approach separates the UI's presentation logic from its underlying implementation, offering significant advantages in terms of flexibility, maintainability, and scalability. 
Key Principles of Config-Driven UI:
Separation of Concerns: The UI's definition (what it looks like and how it behaves) is distinct from the code that renders it.
External Configuration: UI elements, their properties, and interactions are described in external formats like JSON, YAML, or XML.
Dynamic Generation: A core UI engine or renderer interprets the configuration and dynamically constructs the user interface at runtime.
Benefits of Config-Driven UI:
Flexibility and Adaptability: UI changes can be implemented by modifying configuration files without requiring code changes or redeployments. This allows for rapid iteration and customization for different user groups, locales, or business requirements.
Faster Development: Reusable UI components and configurations can accelerate the development of new features and interfaces.
Improved Maintainability: Centralized configuration makes it easier to manage and update UI elements across an application or suite of applications.
Reduced Development Costs: Less code to write and maintain can translate to lower development and maintenance expenses.
Enhanced Scalability: CDUI facilitates the creation of complex, data-driven interfaces and dashboards that can adapt to varying data structures and user needs.
Examples of Config-Driven UI Applications:
Dynamic Forms: Building forms where fields, validations, and layout are defined in a configuration.
Content Management Systems (CMS): Defining page layouts, component arrangements, and content types through configurations.
Dashboards and Reporting Tools: Creating customizable dashboards where widgets and data visualizations are configured.
A/B Testing: Easily switching between different UI variations for testing purposes by modifying configurations.
Implementation Considerations:
Configuration Format: Choosing an appropriate format (JSON, YAML, etc.) for defining UI elements and their properties.
UI Engine/Renderer: Developing or utilizing a framework that can interpret the configuration and render the corresponding UI components.
Component Library: Creating a library of reusable UI components that can be referenced and configured.
Validation and Error Handling: Implementing mechanisms to validate configurations and handle errors during UI generation.


This JSON you shared is a Swiggy API response (from their internal dapi endpoints).
Let me break it down for you step by step üëá

üìå Structure

The outer object:

{
  statusCode: 0,
  data: { ... },
  tid: "...",
  sid: "...",
  deviceId: "...",
  csrfToken: "..."
}


statusCode: 0 ‚Üí means the request was successful.

data ‚Üí contains the actual content (filters, restaurant list, etc.).

tid, sid, deviceId, csrfToken ‚Üí Swiggy tracking/session info.

üìå Inside data

The data object holds Swiggy‚Äôs restaurant listing for a given location or search.

statusMessage: "done successfully"
Confirms the request worked.

cards ‚Üí This is the main array where Swiggy packs UI widgets (filters, sorting, restaurants, etc.).

üìå Example of Cards
üîπ Filters (InlineViewFilterSortWidget)
{
  "@type": "swiggy.gandalf.widgets.v2.InlineViewFilterSortWidget",
  "restaurantCount": 214,
  "facetList": [
    {
      "label": "Veg/Non-Veg",
      "facetInfo": [
        { "label": "Non Veg" },
        { "label": "Pure Veg" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "label": "Ratings",
      "facetInfo": [
        { "label": "Ratings 4.0+" },
        { "label": "Ratings 4.5+" }
      ]
    }
  ]
}


üëâ This tells the app which filters to show (Veg, Non-Veg, Ratings, Cost, Delivery Time, etc.).

üîπ Restaurant Count Widget
{
  "@type": "swiggy.gandalf.widgets.v2.GridWidget",
  "id": "restaurantCountWidget",
  "gridElements": {
    "infoWithStyle": {
      "text": "214 Restaurants to explore"
    }
  }
}


üëâ Just displays "214 Restaurants to explore" in the UI.

üîπ Restaurant Info (Restaurant)
{
  "@type": "swiggy.presentation.food.v2.Restaurant",
  "info": {
    "id": "787489",
    "name": "FreshMenu",
    "locality": "BANASWADI",
    "areaName": "OMBR LAYOUT",
    "costForTwo": "‚Çπ250 for two",
    "cuisines": [
      "Continental", "Chinese", "Oriental"
    ],
    "avgRating": 3.8,
    "sla": { "deliveryTime": 33, "slaString": "30-35 mins" },
    "availability": { "opened": true },
    "aggregatedDiscountInfoV3": {
      "header": "ITEMS",
      "subHeader": "AT ‚Çπ39"
    }
  },
  "cta": {
    "link": "swiggy://menu?restaurant_id=787489&query=Chinese",
    "text": "RESTAURANT_MENU"
  }
}


üëâ This is one restaurant card:

id: unique restaurant ID.

name: "FreshMenu".

location: "BANASWADI".

costForTwo: "‚Çπ250 for two".

rating: 3.8.

sla: delivery time details.

discounts: "ITEMS AT ‚Çπ39".

cta: deep link to open restaurant menu.

üìå Other Important Fields

promoted / adTrackingId ‚Üí for paid promotions.

badges ‚Üí extra tags like ‚ÄúPure Veg‚Äù, ‚ÄúTop Rated‚Äù.

sla ‚Üí delivery SLA (time, distance).

aggregatedDiscountInfoV3 ‚Üí offers like 20% OFF, ITEMS AT ‚Çπ99.

‚úÖ So, this JSON is the payload Swiggy‚Äôs mobile/web app uses to build the "restaurants list" page.

If you parse this, you can build your own restaurant listing UI ‚Äî filters at the top, then the restaurant cards (name, cuisines, ratings, price, delivery time, offers).


